The Rockets football season officially starts August 10th! But there is a conditioning event today from 5:30-7pm.Monday -Thursday, from 5-7:30pm and then 1-3:30pm on Friday. You can find the questionnaire on the Kelloggsville Athletic website!

post_text:
We are all aware of the challenges that schools face planning for the upcoming year. In addition, there are many "unknowns" and potential situations that have made it difficult to understand the direction we as a state and country are headed.

At Kelloggsville Public Schools, we have decided to give our families, our community, a choice of what learning option works best for each individual family, whether it be completely online or in-person learning model. If in-person learning is the best choice for your family, and your student(s) require transportation, please be assured we are adhering to the State of Michigan safety protocols, doing everything we can to make our buses as safe as possible.

â€œItâ€™s been eight years since I first stepped foot in a Boys & Girls Club. Since Iâ€™ve been attending the Boys & Girls Club, I have built relationships with the staff. February 27 at 7:49 PM Â·

Thank you to Mercantile Bank of Michigan for donating a CPR in Schools kit to the students at Kelloggsville Public Schools.

More than 326,000 people experience cardiac arrest outside of a hospital each year, and about 90 percent of those victims die, often because bystanders donâ€™t know how to start CPR or are afraid theyâ€™ll do something wrong. CPR, especially if performed immediately, can double or triple a cardiac arrest victimâ€™s chance of survival.

We know that Kelloggsville students will be prepared. #CPRMI

post_text: These cities and the Rapid are looking for members of our community to join them in discussing developments of South Division Ave and the Silver Line in our neighborhoods! Take a look at the City of Kentwood post for the events created for each workshop.
shared_text:
City of Kentwood
February 12 at 3:51 PM Â·

The City of Kentwood, The City of Grand Rapids and City of Wyoming - City Hall, in partnership with The Rapid, are collaborating on a project to align development priorities and plans on South Division Avenue. Building off of current and completed neighborhood and master plans, the partners are creating strategies for leveraging the Silver Line as a tool for economic development.

This project relies heavily on input from residents, business owners and stakeholder groups along and near the Division corridor. We welcome you to join us at four upcoming workshops this month:

1) Feb. 27 Division Avenue Design Workshop at Supermercado Mexico
2) Feb. 27 Division Avenue Design Workshop at Golden Bridge Market
3) Feb. 28 Division Avenue Design Workshop at New Beginnings
4) Feb. 28 Division Avenue Design Workshop at Brann's Steakhouse & Grille

The events are the start of a broad outreach and engagement plan to understand what the community would like to see for the future of Division Avenue. See you there!

After 31 years of coaching with the Kelloggsville Football program, 30 of those as head coach, Don Galster has decided to hang up his whistle and headset.

Our Board of Education and administration team recognized Mr. Galster at the BOE meeting last night for the time and dedication he gave to our football program these last three decades. Thank you so much Mr. Galster, for everything you have provided our students on and off the field during your time at Kelloggsville!

post_text: Today may have been the first snowfall of November, but our KECLC students have been learning about fall! Students learned the stages of a pumpkin by singing Life Cycle of a Pumpkin. After that, they opened up a pumpkin to discover the seeds and fibers inside. And to end the pumpkin investigation they did a science experiment and erupted a pumpkin! They added baking soda and vinegar into the pumpkin and watched it bubble over the top of the pumpkin. This was a very exciting experiment and the students asked to see the eruption over and over again!
text: Today may have been the first snowfall of November, but our KECLC students have been learning about fall! Students learned the stages of a pumpkin by singing Life Cycle of a Pumpkin. After that, they opened up a pumpkin to discover the seeds and fibers inside. And to end the pumpkin investigation they did a science experiment and erupted a pumpkin! They added baking soda and vinegar into the pumpkin and watched it bubble over the top of the pumpkin. This was a very exciting experiment and the students asked to see the eruption over and over again!
